   = \n| totalv18  = \n\n| title19   = [[#ep63|Robin Hood Rescues]]\n| date19    = {{Start date|2020|5|1}}\n| rs19      = \n| viewers19 = \n| dvr19     = \n| dvrv19    = \n| total19   = \n| totalv19  = \n\n| title20   = [[#ep64| ]]\n| date20    = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| rs20      = \n| viewers20 = \n| dvr20     = \n| dvrv20    = \n| total20   = \n| totalv20  =\n\n| title21   = [[#ep65| ]]\n| date21    = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| rs21      = \n| viewers21 = \n| dvr21     = \n| dvrv21    = \n| total21   = \n| totalv21  = \n\n| title22   = [[#ep66| ]]\n| date22    = {{Start date|2020||}}\n| rs22      = \n| viewers22 = \n| dvr22     = \n| dvrv22    = \n| total22   = \n| totalv22  = -->\n}}\n\n<!--===Critical response===\n\n===Accolades===\n-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.cwtv.com/shows/dynasty/}}\n* {{IMDb episodes|6128300|Dynasty}}\n\n{{Dynasty}}\n\n[[Category:2019 American television seasons]]\n[[Category:2020 American television seasons]]\n[[Category:Dynasty (2017 TV series) seasons]]\n[[Category:Television production suspended due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "YoungForever", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update; aired [62]", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynasty_(2017_TV_series,_season_3)"}
{"title_page": "Ricky Santos", "text_new": "{{short description|American football player}}\n{{Infobox CFL biography\n| name = Ricky Santos\n| image =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1984|4|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Norwood, Massachusetts]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| team =\n| number =\n| status =\n| import = yes\n| position1 = Quarterback\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 2\n| weight_lb = 205\n| college = [[New Hampshire Wildcats|New Hampshire]]\n| high_school = [[Bellingham High School (Bellingham, Massachusetts)|Bellingham (MA)]]\n| hand = right\n| playing_years1 = 2008\n| playing_team1 = [[Kansas City Chiefs]]*\n| playing_years2 = {{CFL Year|2008}}\u2013{{CFL Year|2009}}\n| playing_team2 = [[Montreal Alouettes]]\n| playing_years3 = {{CFL Year|2009}}\n| playing_team3 = [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]\n| playing_years4 = {{CFL Year|2010}}\u2013{{CFL Year|2011}}\n| playing_team4 = Montreal Alouettes\n| playing_years5 = {{CFL Year|2012}}\n| playing_team5 = [[Toronto Argonauts]]*\n| career_footnotes = <nowiki/>*Offseason and/or practice squad member only\n| career_highlights = * 3x [[All-America]]n (2005-2007)\n* 3\u00d7 All-[[Atlantic 10 Conference|Atlantic 10]] (2004-2006)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Atlantic 10 Conference|Atlantic 10]] Offensive Player of the Year (2005, 2006)\n* All-[[Colonial Athletic Association|CAA]] (2007)\n* [[Colonial Athletic Association|CAA]] Co-Offensive Player of the Year (2007)\n* [[Walter Payton Award]] (2006)\n* [[Eastern College Athletic Conference|ECAC]] Rookie of the Year (2004)\n* [[Atlantic 10 Conference|Atlantic 10]] Co-Rookie of the Year (2004)\n| module = {{Infobox college coach|embed=yes\n| coach_years1 = 2012\n| coach_team1 = [[Bellingham High School (Bellingham, Massachusetts)|Bellingham HS]] (asst.)\n| coach_years2 = 2013\u20132015\n| coach_team2 = [[New Hampshire Wildcats football|New Hampshire]] (wide receivers)\n| coach_years3 = 2016\u20132018\n| coach_team3 = [[Columbia Lions football|Columbia]] (quarterbacks)\n| coach_years4 = 2019\u2013present\n| coach_team4 = New Hampshire (interim HC)\n| overall_record = 6\u20135\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships =\n}}\n}}\n'''Ricky Santos''' (born April 26, 1984) is an American former [[gridiron football]] [[quarterback]] who is currently the interim head coach of the [[New Hampshire Wildcats football]] team. He played [[college football]] at New Hampshire, and was signed by the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 2008.\n\n==Early years==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=February 2020}}\nSantos attended [[Bellingham High School (Massachusetts)|Bellingham High School]] in [[Bellingham, Massachusetts]], and was a letterman in football, basketball, baseball, and track and field. In football, he was a two-time Tri-Valley League MVP, was twice named the Division V Player of the Year,a two-time [[MetroWest]] Player of the Year, and as a senior, won all-State honors. In November 2002, during the first annual Thanksgiving Day game against Norton, he threw for seven touchdown passes, which is still one of the best high school performances in Bellingham history. He broke the state touchdown record and led his teams to two Massachusetts High School Super Bowl titles (2000 and 2001). He graduated from Bellingham High in 2003.\n\n==College career==\nSantos attended the University of New Hampshire and was a four-year starter at quarterback.  During his time, the Wildcats went a combined 37\u201314, winning one [[Atlantic 10 Conference|Atlantic 10]] Football Conference Championship, two Northern Division Championships, and made the [[NCAA Division I Football Championship|NCAA I-AA/FCS]] Playoffs all four seasons.  A three-time All-America selection, Santos won the [[Walter Payton Award]] in 2006, as the top offensive player in FCS (formerly Division I-AA).  Santos finished his college career third on the NCAA all-time career passing yardage list with 13,212 yards, and third on the NCAA all-time list for career touchdown passes with 123.  After the 2007 season, his no. 2 jersey was retired by New Hampshire.<ref>[http://www.unhwildcats.com/index.cfm?id=ca22c91e-dee5-8060-5375830a0f23f4aa&pid=902E37C0-FB8E-EB1C-3C20613614DB878F&archive=0/ Football players honored at award banquet and Santos' jersey retired<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n;Kansas City Chiefs\nAfter going undrafted in the [[2008 NFL Draft]], Santos agreed to join the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in May. However, he was released the same month.\n\n;Montreal Alouettes\nIn May 2008, Santos was signed by the [[Montreal Alouettes]] of the [[Canadian Football League]].\n\n;Winnipeg Blue Bombers\nOn September 21, 2009, the [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]] acquired Santos from the [[Montreal Alouettes]] in exchange for non-import [[defensive ends]] [[Riall Johnson]] and [[Shawn Mayne]].<ref name=\"Tait\">{{cite news|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/football/bombers/blue-make-yet-another-move-at-qb-60187182.html|title=Blue make yet another move at QB|last=Tait|first=Ed|date=2009-09-22|work=Winnipeg Free Press|accessdate=2009-09-23}}</ref> He was released by the Blue Bombers on May 17, 2010.<ref>http://www.torontosun.com/sports/football/2010/05/17/13983881.html</ref>\n\n;Montreal Alouettes (second stint)\nAfter an injury to [[Adrian McPherson]], the Montreal Alouettes re-signed Santos on June 22, 2010 to serve as the third-string quarterback.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20120220051917/http://en.montrealalouettes.com/roster/show/id/1467</ref> On June 9, 2012, he was released by the Alouettes.<ref>http://blogs.montrealgazette.com/2012/06/09/bowman-suffers-knee-injury/</ref>\n\n;Toronto Argonauts\nOn June 16, 2012, Santos was signed by the [[Toronto Argonauts]].<ref>http://www.argonauts.ca/article/argos-add-qb-ricky-santos ARGOS ADD QB RICKY SANTOS</ref> He was released four days later.<ref name=\"Christie\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/football/quarterback-ricky-santos-among-players-released-by-argos/article4357942/ | title=Quarterback Ricky Santos among players released by Argos | work=[[The Globe and Mail]] | agency=June 20, 2012 | accessdate=June 21, 2012 | author=Christie, James}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nSantos was quarterbacks coach for three seasons (2016\u20132018) with the [[Columbia Lions football|Columbia Lions]].<ref name=UNHbio>{{cite web |url=https://unhwildcats.com/staff.aspx?staff=46 |title=Ricky Santos - Staff Directory - University of New Hampshire |website=unhwildcats.com |accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSantos joined the New Hampshire coaching staff in March 2019, as associate head coach and quarterbacks coach.<ref name=UNHbio/> When Wildcats head coach [[Sean McDonnell]] took a leave of absence for health reasons in late August 2019, Santos was named interim head coach for the team.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/08/27/new-hampshire-football-coach-sean-mcdonnell-on-leave-for-health-reasons/ |title=New Hampshire football coach Sean McDonnell on leave for health reasons |first=John |last=Connolly |website=[[Boston Herald]] |url-access=limited |date=August 27, 2019 |accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref> The [[2019 New Hampshire Wildcats football team|2019 Wildcats]] finished with a record of 6\u20135.\n\n===Head coaching record===\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[New Hampshire Wildcats football|New Hampshire Wildcats]]\n | conf      = [[Colonial Athletic Association]]\n | startyear = 2019\n | endyear   = \n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[2019 NCAA Division I FCS football season|2019]]\n | name         = [[2019 New Hampshire Wildcats football team|New Hampshire]]{{double dagger}}\n | overall      = 6\u20135\n | conference   = 5\u20133\n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = \n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = New Hampshire\n | overall    = 6\u20135\n | confrecord = 5\u20133\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 6\u20135\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n}}\n{{double dagger}} Interim head coach\n\n==Personal life==\nSantos is a cousin of racecar driver [[Bobby Santos III]].{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120220051917/http://en.montrealalouettes.com/roster/show/id/1467 Montreal Alouettes bio]\n* [https://unhwildcats.com/staff.aspx?staff=46 New Hampshire Wildcats bio]\n\n{{Walter Payton Award}}\n{{New Hampshire Wildcats football coach navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santos, Ricky}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:American people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Columbia Lions football coaches]]\n[[Category:High school football coaches in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:New Hampshire Wildcats football coaches]]\n[[Category:New Hampshire Wildcats football players]]\n[[Category:People from Norwood, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Walter Payton Award winners]]\n[[Category:Winnipeg Blue Bombers players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football player}}\n{{Infobox CFL biography\n| name = Ricky Santos\n| image =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1984|4|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Norwood, Massachusetts]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| team =\n| number =\n| status =\n| import = yes\n| position1 = Quarterback\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 2\n| weight_lb = 205\n| college = [[New Hampshire Wildcats|New Hampshire]]\n| high_school = [[Bellingham High School (Bellingham, Massachusetts)|Bellingham (MA)]]\n| hand = right\n| playing_years1 = 2008\n| playing_team1 = [[Kansas City Chiefs]]*\n| playing_years2 = {{CFL Year|2008}}\u2013{{CFL Year|2009}}\n| playing_team2 = [[Montreal Alouettes]]\n| playing_years3 = {{CFL Year|2009}}\n| playing_team3 = [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]]\n| playing_years4 = {{CFL Year|2010}}\u2013{{CFL Year|2011}}\n| playing_team4 = Montreal Alouettes\n| playing_years5 = {{CFL Year|2012}}\n| playing_team5 = [[Toronto Argonauts]]*\n| career_footnotes = <nowiki/>*Offseason and/or practice squad member only\n| career_highlights = * 3x [[All-America]]n (2005-2007)\n* 3\u00d7 All-[[Atlantic 10 Conference|Atlantic 10]] (2004-2006)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Atlantic 10 Conference|Atlantic 10]] Offensive Player of the Year (2005, 2006)\n* All-[[Colonial Athletic Association|CAA]] (2007)\n* [[Colonial Athletic Association|CAA]] Co-Offensive Player of the Year (2007)\n* [[Walter Payton Award]] (2006)\n* [[Eastern College Athletic Conference|ECAC]] Rookie of the Year (2004)\n* [[Atlantic 10 Conference|Atlantic 10]] Co-Rookie of the Year (2004)\n| module = {{Infobox college coach|embed=yes\n| coach_years1 = 2012\n| coach_team1 = [[Bellingham High School (Bellingham, Massachusetts)|Bellingham HS]] (asst.)\n| coach_years2 = 2013\u20132015\n| coach_team2 = [[New Hampshire Wildcats football|New Hampshire]] (wide receivers)\n| coach_years3 = 2016\u20132018\n| coach_team3 = [[Columbia Lions football|Columbia]] (quarterbacks)\n| coach_years4 = 2019\u2013present\n| coach_team4 = New Hampshire (interim HC)\n| overall_record = 6\u20135\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships =\n}}\n}}\n'''Ricky Santos''' (born April 26, 1984) is an American former [[gridiron football]] [[quarterback]] who is currently the interim head coach of the [[New Hampshire Wildcats football]] team. He played [[college football]] at New Hampshire, and was signed by the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 2008.\n\n==Early years==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=February 2020}}\nSantos attended [[Bellingham High School (Massachusetts)|Bellingham High School]] in [[Bellingham, Massachusetts]], and was a letterman in football, basketball, baseball, and track and field. In football, he was a two-time Tri-Valley League MVP, was twice named the Division V Player of the Year,a two-time [[MetroWest]] Player of the Year, and as a senior, won all-State honors. In November 2002, during the first annual Thanksgiving Day game against Norton, he threw for seven touchdown passes, which is still one of the best high school performances in Bellingham history. He broke the state touchdown record and led his teams to two Massachusetts High School Super Bowl titles (2000 and 2001). He graduated from Bellingham High in 2003.\n\n==College career==\nSantos attended the University of New Hampshire and was a four-year starter at quarterback.  During his time, the Wildcats went a combined 37\u201314, winning one [[Atlantic 10 Conference|Atlantic 10]] Football Conference Championship, two Northern Division Championships, and made the [[NCAA Division I Football Championship|NCAA I-AA/FCS]] Playoffs all four seasons.  A three-time All-America selection, Santos won the [[Walter Payton Award]] in 2006, as the top offensive player in FCS (formerly Division I-AA).  Santos finished his college career third on the NCAA all-time career passing yardage list with 13,212 yards, and third on the NCAA all-time list for career touchdown passes with 123.  After the 2007 season, his no. 2 jersey was retired by New Hampshire.<ref>[http://www.unhwildcats.com/index.cfm?id=ca22c91e-dee5-8060-5375830a0f23f4aa&pid=902E37C0-FB8E-EB1C-3C20613614DB878F&archive=0/ Football players honored at award banquet and Santos' jersey retired<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n;Kansas City Chiefs\nAfter going undrafted in the [[2008 NFL Draft]], Santos agreed to join the [[Kansas City Chiefs]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in May. However, he was released the same month.\n\n;Montreal Alouettes\nIn May 2008, Santos was signed by the [[Montreal Alouettes]] of the [[Canadian Football League]].\n\n;Winnipeg Blue Bombers\nOn September 21, 2009, the [[Winnipeg Blue Bombers]] acquired Santos from the [[Montreal Alouettes]] in exchange for non-import [[defensive ends]] [[Riall Johnson]] and [[Shawn Mayne]].<ref name=\"Tait\">{{cite news|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/sports/football/bombers/blue-make-yet-another-move-at-qb-60187182.html|title=Blue make yet another move at QB|last=Tait|first=Ed|date=2009-09-22|work=Winnipeg Free Press|accessdate=2009-09-23}}</ref> He was released by the Blue Bombers on May 17, 2010.<ref>http://www.torontosun.com/sports/football/2010/05/17/13983881.html</ref>\n\n;Montreal Alouettes (second stint)\nAfter an injury to [[Adrian McPherson]], the Montreal Alouettes re-signed Santos on June 22, 2010 to serve as the third-string quarterback.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20120220051917/http://en.montrealalouettes.com/roster/show/id/1467</ref> On June 9, 2012, he was released by the Alouettes.<ref>http://blogs.montrealgazette.com/2012/06/09/bowman-suffers-knee-injury/</ref>\n\n;Toronto Argonauts\nOn June 16, 2012, Santos was signed by the [[Toronto Argonauts]].<ref>http://www.argonauts.ca/article/argos-add-qb-ricky-santos ARGOS ADD QB RICKY SANTOS</ref> He was released four days later.<ref name=\"Christie\">{{cite news | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/football/quarterback-ricky-santos-among-players-released-by-argos/article4357942/ | title=Quarterback Ricky Santos among players released by Argos | work=[[The Globe and Mail]] | agency=June 20, 2012 | accessdate=June 21, 2012 | author=Christie, James}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nSantos was quarterbacks coach for three seasons (2016\u20132018) with the [[Columbia Lions football|Columbia Lions]].<ref name=UNHbio>{{cite web |url=https://unhwildcats.com/staff.aspx?staff=46 |title=Ricky Santos - Staff Directory - University of New Hampshire |website=unhwildcats.com |accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSantos joined the New Hampshire coaching staff in March 2019, as associate head coach and quarterbacks coach.<ref name=UNHbio/> When Wildcats head coach [[Sean McDonnell]] took a leave of absence for health reasons in late August 2019, Santos was named interim head coach for the team.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bostonherald.com/2019/08/27/new-hampshire-football-coach-sean-mcdonnell-on-leave-for-health-reasons/ |title=New Hampshire football coach Sean McDonnell on leave for health reasons |first=John |last=Connolly |website=[[Boston Herald]] |url-access=limited |date=August 27, 2019 |accessdate=February 17, 2020}}</ref> The [[2019 New Hampshire Wildcats football team|2019 Wildcats]] finished with a record of 6\u20135.\n\n===Head coaching record===\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[New Hampshire Wildcats football|New Hampshire Wildcats]]\n | conf      = [[Colonial Athletic Association]]\n | startyear = 2019\n | endyear   = \n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[2019 NCAA Division I FCS football season|2019]]\n | name         = [[2019 New Hampshire Wildcats football team|New Hampshire]]{{double dagger}}\n | overall      = 6\u20135\n | conference   = 5\u20133\n | confstanding = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = \n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = New Hampshire\n | overall    = 6\u20135\n | confrecord = 5\u20133\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 6\u20135\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n}}\n{{double dagger}} Interim head coach\n\n==Personal life==\nSantos is a cousin of racecar driver [[Bobby Santos III]].{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120220051917/http://en.montrealalouettes.com/roster/show/id/1467 Montreal Alouettes bio]\n* [https://unhwildcats.com/staff.aspx?staff=46 New Hampshire Wildcats bio]\n\n{{Walter Payton Award}}\n{{New Hampshire Wildcats football coach navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Santos, Ricky}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:American people of Portuguese descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Columbia Lions football coaches]]\n[[Category:High school football coaches in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Kansas City Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:New Hampshire Wildcats football coaches]]\n[[Category:New Hampshire Wildcats football players]]\n[[Category:People from Norwood, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Walter Payton Award winners]]\n[[Category:Winnipeg Blue Bombers players]]\n", "name_user": "Jweiss11", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ricky_Santos"}
{"title_page": "Spiderland", "text_new": "{{short description|Album}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Spiderland\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Slint]]\n| cover      = Slint - Spiderland.jpg\n| alt        = A black-and-white photograph of Slint standing in tall water with only part of their faces visible\n| released   = {{Start date|1991|3|27|mf=yes}}\n| recorded   = August\u2013October 1990\n| venue      =\n| studio     = {{ubl|[[River North Records]]|{{small|([[Chicago]], [[Illinois]])}}}}\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Post-rock]]\n* [[math rock]]\n* [[post-hardcore]]\n}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=39|s=31}}\n| label      = [[Touch and Go Records|Touch and Go]]\n| producer   = [[Brian Paulson]]\n| prev_title = [[Tweez]]\n| prev_year  = 1989\n| next_title = [[Untitled Slint EP|Untitled]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n}}\n'''''Spiderland''''' is the second and final studio album by the American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Slint]]. It was released on March 27, 1991, through [[Touch and Go Records]]. Featuring dramatically alternating [[Dynamics (music)|dynamics]] and vocals ranging from [[spoken word]] to shouting, the album contains [[narrative]] lyrics that emphasize alienation. ''Spiderland'' was Slint's first release on Touch and Go, and the group's only album to feature bassist Todd Brashear.\n\nAlthough ''Spiderland'' was not widely recognized on its initial release, it eventually sold more than 50,000 copies and became a landmark album in [[underground music]] after Slint broke up. The album has been influential on the styles of many bands in the [[post-rock]] genres. In 2005, 2007 and 2013\u20132014, Slint reunited for a tour consisting of performances of ''Spiderland'' in its entirety.\n\n== Background ==\n\nSlint formed in 1986 in [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], [[Kentucky]], from the remnants of the [[punk rock]] band [[Squirrel Bait]]; the founding members included [[Brian McMahan]] (guitar, vocals), [[David Pajo]] (guitar), [[Britt Walford]] (drums) and [[Ethan Buckler]] (bass guitar). The band's debut album, the [[Steve Albini]]-produced ''[[Tweez]]'', was released on the group's self-owned [[Record label|label]] Jennifer Hartman Records and Tapes.<ref name=\"T&G bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.touchandgorecords.com/bands/band.php?id=70 |title=Slint <nowiki>|</nowiki> Touch and Go / Quarterstick Records |work=touchandgorecords.com |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref> The album's sound has been described as a combination of \"scratchy guitars, thumping bass lines and hard hitting drums\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/6290/Slint-Tweez/ |title=Slint \u2013 ''Tweez'' (Album Review) <nowiki>|</nowiki> Sputnikmusic |last=Jackson |first=Chris |date=April 16, 2006 |work=[[Sputnikmusic]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref> Buckler promptly left the band out of dissatisfaction with Albini's production, and was replaced with Todd Brashear.<ref name=\"musicianguide\" /> The band's second recording was for the [[instrumental]] [[extended play]] ''[[Slint (EP)|Slint]]'', which included a new version of \"Rhoda\" from ''Tweez''. The EP, which would not be released until 1994, was a departure from ''Tweez''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s sound and reflected the band's new musical direction.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.southern.com/southern/band/SLINT/biog.html |title=Slint |work=[[Southern Records|southern.com]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090716153944/http://www.southern.com/southern/band/SLINT/biog.html |archivedate=July 16, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAfter the band ended its brief tour in support of ''Tweez'', most of its members attended college.<ref name=\"musicianguide\" /> Around this time McMahan and Walford began writing together for the band's next record, creating six new songs which the band practiced throughout the summer of 1990.<ref name=\"musicianguide\" /> Slint entered River North Records in August 1990 to record ''Spiderland''. At that time there were no vocals or lyrics prepared for the album, so the band wrote them while in the studio.<ref name=\"musicianguide\" /> The album's producer, [[Brian Paulson]], was known for his \"live\" recording style in the studio, with minimal [[take]]s.<ref name=\"indyweek\">{{cite web |url=http://www.indyweek.com/gyrobase/Content?oid=oid%3A23657 |title=''Independent Weekly'': Special Issues: Rock & Roll Quarterly: Brian Paulson |last=Parker |first=Chris |date=February 9, 2005 |work=[[Independent Weekly|indyweek.com]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330130145/https://www.indyweek.com/indyweek/brian-paulson/Content?oid=1194172 |archive-date=2018-03-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Paulson recalled \"It was weird while I was doing [''Spiderland''] because I remember sitting there, and I just knew there was something about it. I've never heard anything like this. I'm really digging this but it's really fucking weird.\"<ref name=\"indyweek\" />\n\nThe recording sessions for ''Spiderland'' are reputed to have been difficult for the members of the band and were, according to [[AllMusic]], \"intense, traumatic and one more piece of evidence supporting the theory that band members had to be periodically [[Institutionalisation|institutionalized]] during the completion of the album.\"<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/spiderland-mw0000267497 |title=''Spiderland'' \u2013 Slint : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards : AllMusic |last=Carlson |first=Dean |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616180251/http://www.allmusic.com/album/spiderland-mw0000267497 |archivedate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Rumors circulated that at least one member of Slint had been checked into a [[psychiatric hospital]].<ref name=\"p. 640\" /> Walford later addressed these stories in an article in ''[[Select (magazine)|Select]]'' by saying, \"[We were] definitely trying to be serious about things, pretty intense, which made recording the album kinda stressful.\"<ref name=\"p. 640\" /> The recording was completed in four days.<ref name=\"indyweek\" />\n\n== Music ==\n\n{{Listen\n |filename = Breadcrumb Trail - Slint.ogg\n |title = \"Breadcrumb Trail\"\n |description = A sample of \"Breadcrumb Trail\", the [[opening track]] from Slint's 1991 album, ''Spiderland''. This sample contains part of the song's verse, bridge, and chorus.\n |filename2 = Good Morning Captain - Slint.ogg\n |title2 = \"Good Morning, Captain\"\n |description2 = A sample of \"Good Morning, Captain\", the sixth track from ''Spiderland''. This sample contains part of the song's second verse.\n}}\n\nThe music of ''Spiderland'' is noted for its angular guitar rhythms, dramatically alternating [[Dynamics (music)|dynamic]] shifts and irregular [[time signature]]s. McMahan's singing style interchanges between mumbling [[spoken word]] and strained shouting. The lyrics of ''Spiderland'' are often written in a [[narrative]] style. Influences on the record included [[Gang of Four (band)|Gang of Four]], [[Black Sabbath]] and [[Sonic Youth]].<ref name=\"Guardian Camber Sands Holiday Centre\" /> Will Hermes of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' summarized the album's sound as \"mid-'70s [[King Crimson]] gone [[emo]]: screeching guitar chords and gorgeous note-spinning in odd-metered instrumentals speckled with words both spoken and sung\".<ref name=\"Spin 100\">{{cite journal |last=Hermes |first=Will |date=July 2005 |title=Slint \u2013 ''Spiderland'' |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]}}</ref>\n\nThe album's opening track, \"Breadcrumb Trail\", describes a day spent at a carnival with a [[Fortune-telling|fortune-teller]].<ref name=\"Breadcrumb Trail\" /> The song features a complex arrangement with sharp transitions, and the guitar fluctuates between a clean-sounding [[riff]] with [[harmonic]]s in the [[Verse (music)|verse]] to heavy [[Distortion (guitar)|distortion]] featuring extremely high-pitched notes in the [[Song structure (popular music)#Chorus|chorus]].<ref name=\"Breadcrumb Trail\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/breadcrumb-trail-mt0008849294 |title=Breadcrumb Trail \u2013 Slint : Listen, Appearances, Song Review : AllMusic |last=Maginnis |first=Tom |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"Nosferatu Man\", the second track, is inspired by the 1922 [[German Expressionism|German Expressionist]] [[silent film]] ''[[Nosferatu]]''.<ref name=\"Nosferatu Man\" /> The song's verse includes a [[Consonance and dissonance|dissonant]] guitar riff, which uses high-pitched notes similar to those in \"Breadcrumb Trail\" and a drumbeat based on [[snare drum|snare]] and [[Tom-tom drum|toms]], absent of [[cymbal]]s.<ref name=\"Nosferatu Man\" /> The chorus, featuring \"jagged\" distorted guitar and a beat with \"thrashing cymbals with quick [[Fill (music)|drum fills]]\", segues into an extended [[Jam session|jam]] before the song ends with 30 seconds of [[Audio feedback|feedback]].<ref name=\"Nosferatu Man\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/nosferatu-man-mt0000860534 |title=Nosferatu Man \u2013 Slint : Listen, Appearances, Song Review : AllMusic |last=Maginnis |first=Tom |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"Don, Aman\" features Walford on lead vocals and guitar. Delivered in a hushed tone, the song's ambiguous lyrics depict the thoughts of an \"isolated soul\" before, after and during an evening at a bar.<ref name=\"Don, Aman\" /> The [[tempo]] quickens throughout, and then becomes loud and distorted before slowing back to the original tempo.<ref name=\"Don, Aman\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/don-aman-mt0000298526 |title=Don, Aman \u2013 Slint : Listen, Appearances, Song Review : AllMusic |last=Maginnis |first=Tom |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"Washer\", the album's longest track, features a \"barely audible\" intro with guitar and cymbals before the rest of the band comes in.<ref name=\"Washer\" /> The song builds tension until the final verse, which features loud distortion, and is followed by a lengthy [[Conclusion (music)|outro]].<ref name=\"Washer\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/washer-mt0004679278 |title=Washer \u2013 Slint : Listen, Appearances, Song Review : AllMusic |last=Maginnis |first=Tom |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"For Dinner...\" is an [[instrumental]] track.<ref name=\"For Dinner\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/for-dinner-mt0003956572 |title=For Dinner... \u2013 Slint : Listen, Appearances, Song Review : AllMusic |last=Maginnis |first=Tom |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref> Beginning with a quiet section of \"brooding chords throb[bing] with the occasional rumble of muted toms and bass drum\", the song cycles through sections of building and releasing tension.<ref name=\"For Dinner\" />\n\nThe final song of the album, \"Good Morning, Captain\", is a tribute to the [[Samuel Taylor Coleridge]] poem ''[[The Rime of the Ancient Mariner]]''.<ref name=\"Good Morning Captain\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/good-morning-captain-mt0001620569 |title=Good Morning Captain \u2013 Slint : Listen, Appearances, Song Review : AllMusic |last=Maginnis |first=Tom |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref> The song features a two chord guitar structure, a \"spindly, tight riff\" from the rhythm section and a \"jerky\" beat.<ref name=\"Good Morning Captain\" /> During the recording of the song's final chorus, McMahan became physically sick due to the strain of yelling over the guitars.<ref name=\"p. 640\" /> David Peschek of ''[[The Guardian]]'' compared \"Good Morning, Captain\" to [[Led Zeppelin]]'s \"[[Stairway to Heaven]]\", writing that \"the extraordinary Good Morning Captain is [Slint's] Stairway to Heaven, if it's possible to imagine Stairway to Heaven bleached of all bombast.\"<ref name=\"Guardian Camber Sands Holiday Centre\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/feb/28/popandrock.alltomorrowsparties |title=Slint, Camber Sands Holiday Centre <nowiki>| Music |</nowiki> ''The Guardian'' |last=Peschek |first=David |date=February 28, 2005 |work=[[The Guardian|guardian.co.uk]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn the iTunes edition of the album, an additional track is added to the end of the album, entitled \"Utica Quarry, Nighttime\". The track is, simply, 15 minutes of field recordings of Utica Quarry, the same place where the photos for Spiderland were taken.\n\n== Title and packaging ==\n\n[[Image:Slint - Spiderland promo.JPG|thumb|Slint in a photo taken by [[Will Oldham]] from the same session as the ''Spiderland'' cover<ref name=\"Southern Gallery\">{{cite web |url=http://www.southern.com/southern/band/SLINT/gallery.html |title=Slint Gallery |work=[[Southern Records|southern.com]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090803222536/http://www.southern.com/southern/band/SLINT/gallery.html |archivedate=August 3, 2009 }}</ref>]]\n\nThe name ''Spiderland'' originates from McMahan's younger brother, who thought that the record sounded \"spidery\".<ref name=\"p. 640\" /> The album's [[black-and-white]] cover photograph, which depicts the members of the band (Brashear, McMahan, Walford and Pajo, from left to right) treading water in the lake of an abandoned quarry, was taken by [[Will Oldham]].<ref name=\"musicianguide\">{{cite web |url=http://www.musicianguide.com/biographies/1608004609/Slint.html |title=Slint Biography |last=McCarthy |first=Shannon |work=musicianguide.com |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> An article in ''[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]]'' credited the cover for creating a mystique surrounding Slint, noting \"[m]ost people only had seen Slint as four heads floating in a Kentucky quarry on Spiderland's cover. Listeners pondered the band's sparsely adorned black-and-white covers as if they were runes bearing secrets.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Segal |first=Dave |date=March 10, 2005 |title=Web of Influence |newspaper=[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]] |url=http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/Content?oid=20786 |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> Chris Gaerig of the ''[[Michigan Daily]]'' wrote, \"the cover of Slint's masterful ''Spiderland'' captures the joyous fear and violence of the album so precisely it shakes souls. The group\u2014submerged in a lake to their chins with deranged smiles\u2014seems to be stalking you, hovering out of the black-and-white fa\u00e7ade.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://media.www.michigandaily.com/media/storage/paper851/news/2007/09/20/TheBSide/Cover.Stories-2980669.shtml |title=Cover Stories \u2013 The B-Side |last=Gaerig |first=Chris |date=September 20, 2007 |work=[[Michigan Daily|michigandaily.com]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080220222104/http://media.www.michigandaily.com/media/storage/paper851/news/2007/09/20/TheBSide/Cover.Stories-2980669.shtml |archivedate=February 20, 2008 }}</ref> Several other promotional images have been taken from the same photo session with Oldham.<ref name=\"Southern Gallery\" />\n\nA photo of a [[spider]] taken by Noel Saltzman is used on the back cover, reflecting the album's title. The inside sleeve contains the message \"interested female vocalists write 1864 douglas blvd. louisville, ky. 40205\". McMahan confirmed that this message was serious, and said \"We did get some responses and we did listen to CDs and tapes. We didn't end up doing anything immediately, so that idea of adding someone sort of fell by the wayside.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Simigis |first=Antonia |date=July 12, 2007 |title=On the record: Slint |newspaper=Time Out Chicago}}</ref> The message \"this recording is meant to be listened to on vinyl\" is printed on some [[Compact Disc|CD]] issues of ''Spiderland'', demonstrating Slint's preference of [[analog signal|analog]] audio devices.<ref name=\"DLB\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dontlookbackconcerts.com/dlbarchive/dlb2007archive/slint/review |title=Don't Look Back \u2013 Don't Look Back 2007 \u2013 Slint \u2013 Review |work=don'tlookbackconcerts.com |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1       = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score  = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic2\">{{cite web|last=Deming|first=Mark|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/spiderland-mw0000267497|title=''Spiderland'' \u2013 Slint : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards : AllMusic|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n| rev2       = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2Score  = A<ref>{{cite web|last=Eakin|first=Marah|url=http://www.avclub.com/review/slints-spiderland-box-rewards-patient-listeners-pa-203207|title=Slint's Spiderland box rewards patient listeners, patient fans|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=April 15, 2014|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev3       = ''[[Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s|Christgau's Consumer Guide]]''\n| rev3Score  = C+<ref name=\"RCreview\"/>\n| rev4       = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev4Score  = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer)|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|edition=5th concise|year=2011|isbn=0-85712-595-8}}</ref>\n| rev5       = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n| rev5Score  = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Male|first=Andrew|title=Slint: Spiderland|journal=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]|issue=246|date=May 2014}}</ref>\n| rev6       = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| Rev6Score  = 10/10<ref name=\"p4k-reissue\">{{cite web|last=Berman|first=Stuart|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19182-slint-spiderland-remastered-box-set/|title=Slint: Spiderland|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=April 16, 2014|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev7       = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev7Score  = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Slint: Spiderland|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|issue=334|date=May 2014|page=124}}</ref>\n| rev8       = ''[[Record Collector]]''\n| rev8Score  = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Atkins|first=Jamie|url=http://recordcollectormag.com/reviews/spiderland|title=Slint \u2013 Spiderland|journal=[[Record Collector]]|issue=426|date=April 2014|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev9       = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev9Score  = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"RSguide\"/>\n| rev10      = ''[[Select (magazine)|Select]]''\n| rev10Score = 4/5<ref name=\"select\">{{cite journal|last=Noon|first=Mike|title=Slint: Spiderland|journal=[[Select (magazine)|Select]]|issue=8|date=February 1991|page=73}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Spiderland'' received widespread critical acclaim from [[music journalism|music critics]], including ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'', ''[[NME]]'', and ''[[The Village Voice]]''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FPmoAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=June 4, 2014|pages=27\u20138|title=Slint's Spiderland|last=Tennent|first=Scott|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury Publishing USA]]|series=[[33\u2153]]|year=2010|isbn=1-4411-9014-7}}</ref> In a contemporary review for ''[[Melody Maker]]'', [[Steve Albini]], producer of Slint's 1989 album ''Tweez'', gave the album ten stars and called it \"a majestic album, sublime and strange, made more brilliant by its simplicity and quiet grace.\" Albini found its unadorned production impeccable and said that it vividly captures McMahan and Pajo's playing so well that their guitars \"seem to hover in space directly past the listener's nose\", while \"the incredibly precise-yet-instinctive drumming has the same range and wallop it would in your living room.\"<ref name=\"melodymaker\">{{cite journal |last=Albini |first=Steve |authorlink=Steve Albini |date=March 30, 1991 |title=<nowiki>[</nowiki>Steve Albini review<nowiki>]</nowiki> |magazine=[[Melody Maker]]}}</ref> ''[[Select (magazine)|Select]]'' noted that the band's popularity in the college circuit was \"probably due to the college circuit celebrity status of their drummer \u2013 Shannon Doughton, aka Britt Walford, the only male member of the 'all-female' indie supergroup [[The Breeders]]\".<ref name=\"select\" /> Their review noted the multiple listens it may take to appreciate it, acknowledging the album as \"immediate as a snail trail to hell, 'Spiderland' needs several plays to burn its way into your consciousness, but when it does...\"<ref name=\"select\" />\n\nIn a retrospective review for [[AllMusic]], Mark Deming said that ''Spiderland'' is \"one of the most important indie albums of the '90s\" and a \"singular achievement\" which found the band \"working with dynamics that made the silences every bit as much presence as the guitars and drums, manipulating space and time as they stretched out and juggled time signatures, and conjuring melodies that were as sparse and fragmented as they were beautiful\".<ref name=\"AllMusic2\"/> [[Robert Christgau]] was less enthusiastic and wrote that, despite their \"sad-sack affect\", Slint are actually \"[[Art rock|art-rockers]] without the courage of their pretensions\" with poor lyrics.<ref name=\"RCreview\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=2000|page=285|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xVQbszFuEGMC&pg=PA285&lpg=PA285#v=onepage&q&f=false|chapter=Slint: Spiderland|title=[[Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s]]|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]|isbn=0-312-24560-2|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref> In ''[[The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]'', ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' journalist Mac Randall felt that the album's music lacks songform, even though it sounds more accessible than ''Tweez'': \"[t]he absence of anything resembling a tune continues to nag.\"<ref name=\"RSguide\">{{cite book |last=Randall |first=Mac |chapter=Slint |editor-last1=Brackett |editor-first1=Nathan |editor-last2=Hoard |editor-first2=Christian |year=2004 |title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]] |location=New York |edition=4th |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |isbn=0-7432-0169-8 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/744 744\u2013745] }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' wrote of ''Spiderland'': \"a heady, chilling listen; the irregularity of its hypnotic melodies, fractured beats and mismatched lyrics demand a new kind of appreciation, independent of traditional notions of songcraft. With its half-mumbled, half-hollered vocals, deliberate percussion and drone-gone-aggressive guitars, ''Spiderland''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s urgency is almost traumatic to swallow: despondency never tasted so real.\" They named it the twelfth best album of the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/5923-top-100-albums-of-the-1990s/9/ |title=Staff Lists: Top 100 Albums of the 1990s <nowiki>| Features |</nowiki> Pitchfork |date=November 17, 2003 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> In 2014, ''Spiderland'' was [[reissue]]d as a [[box set]], featuring 14 previously unreleased tracks, and received widespread critical acclaim; it holds an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 99 out of 100 at [[Metacritic]], based on 11 reviews from mainstream publications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/spiderland-box-set/slint |title=Reviews for Spiderland [Box Set&#93; by Slint |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=June 25, 2014}}</ref> In 2015, ''[[Gigwise]]'' named the album in their list \"The 11 most vicious [[post-hardcore]] albums ever\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gigwise.com/photos/104217/welcome-back-glassjaw:-the-11-most-vicious-post-hardcore-albums-ever|title=Welcome back Glassjaw: The 11 most vicious post-hardcore albums ever|last=Butler|first=Will|date=December 2, 2015|website=[[Gigwise]]|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Legacy ==\n[[Image:Slint at Pitchfork Music Festival.jpg|thumb|Slint performing ''Spiderland'' at the 2007 [[Pitchfork Music Festival]]]]\nThough largely ignored upon its initial release, ''Spiderland'' has attracted greater attention through time. The album has sold over 50,000 copies,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sfj.abstractdynamics.org/archives/006014.html |title=S/FJ: You Thought I Was Backing Out |date=July 25, 2005 |work=abstractdynamics.org |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> though Kory Grow of the ''[[College Music Journal]]'' suggested that the album \"has inspired countless bands (and therefore fans) far beyond its [[Nielsen SoundScan|SoundScan]] numbers\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Grow |first=Kory |date=July 19, 2007 |title=Review: Slint Performs Spiderland in New York |magazine=[[College Music Journal]]}}</ref> ''Spiderland'' has become a landmark indie rock album and is considered, along with [[Talk Talk]]'s ''[[Spirit of Eden]]'' and ''[[Laughing Stock (album)|Laughing Stock]]'', to have been the primary catalyst of the [[post-rock]] genre.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/style/post-rock-ma0000002790 |title=Post-Rock : Significant Albums, Artists and Songs, Most Viewed : AllMusic |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://altmusic.about.com/od/genres/a/post-rock.htm |title=Genre Profile \u2013 Post-Rock |last=Carew |first=Andrew |work=[[About.com]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121118155024/http://altmusic.about.com/od/genres/a/post-rock.htm |archivedate=November 18, 2012 }}</ref> The album is also regarded as being essential to \"the fabric of [[math-rock]] genre\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/3205162-math-rock-family-tree--exploring-the-roots-of-foals | title=Math-Rock Family Tree: exploring the roots of Foals | publisher=[[Drowned in Sound]] | date=April 24, 2008 | accessdate=August 13, 2015 | author=Diver, Mike}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theskinny.co.uk/music/news/slints-spiderland-to-get-deluxe-box-set-reissue | title=Slint's 'Spiderland' to get deluxe box-set reissue | work=[[The Skinny (magazine)|The Skinny]] | date=January 14, 2014 | accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref> David Peschek said that the album is \"the ur-text for what became known as post-rock, a fractured, almost geometric reimagining of rock music stripped of its dionysiac impulse.\"<ref name=\"Guardian Camber Sands Holiday Centre\"/> Rachel Devine of ''[[The List (magazine)|The List]]'' called ''Spiderland'' \"arguably the most disproportionately influential [album] in music history\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.list.co.uk/article/4190-90s-revival/ |title=90s Revival \u2013 Back for Good <nowiki>|</nowiki> ''The List'' |last=Devine |first=Rachel |date=August 16, 2007 |work=[[The List (magazine)|list.co.uk]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> ''Pitchfork'' reviewer Stuart Berman commented: \"''Spiderland''{{'}}s greatest legacy is not that it motivated a cluster of semi-popular bands in the late-90s and early 2000s to adopt its whisper-to-scream schematic. It's the boundless inspiration it perpetually provides for all the bands that have yet to emerge from the basement.\"<ref name=\"p4k-reissue\"/>\n\nMcMahan reflected on the album's success: \"We worked really hard on ''Spiderland''. I mean, I definitely felt much more personal about it. I thought it represented us as people, musically, a lot more than ''Tweez'' did. That's about it. It seemed like when we were around, and actively playing and stuff, that people's responses to us were fairly ambivalent. I thought it was funny when the press picked up on it. For an independent release, it had a strange sort of audience and kept selling three or four years after we recorded it; it still sells more copies than when it first came out.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Modell |first=Josh |date=April 1996 |title=The For Carnation |magazine=Milk |url=http://www.matadorrecords.com/bands/fc/milk.html |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418045221/http://matadorrecords.com/bands/fc/milk.html |archivedate=April 18, 2012 }}</ref> Touch and Go founder Corey Rusk said that ''Spiderland'' is \"like an icon now. But when it came out, nobody cared! The band had broken up by the time the album came out, and it really didn't sell particularly well or get written about all that much in the year it was released. But it was a revolutionary, groundbreaking record, and it's one of the few instances where people catch up to it later on.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/6419-corey-rusk/ |title=Interviews: Corey Rusk <nowiki>| Features |</nowiki> Pitchfork |last=Crock |first=Jason |date=September 5, 2006 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Spiderland'' has also been said by Michael Alan Goldberg to have been a considerable influence on post-rock bands [[Mogwai]], [[Godspeed You! Black Emperor]], [[Isis (band)|Isis]] and [[Explosions in the Sky]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goldberg |first=Michael Alan |date=July 18, 2007 |title=The Last Time We Reunite (Except for That Next Time) |newspaper=[[SF Weekly]]}}</ref> [[Dinosaur Jr]] and [[Sebadoh]] member [[Lou Barlow]] said of ''Spiderland'', \"It was quiet-to-loud without sounding like [[grunge]] or indie rock. It sounded more like a new kind of music.\"<ref name=\"p. 640\">{{cite book |last=Irvin |first=Jim |year=2001 |title=The Mojo Collection: The Greatest Albums of All Time |location=Edinburgh |publisher=Mojo Books |isbn=1-84195-067-X |page=640}}</ref> [[PJ Harvey]] has included ''Spiderland'' in a list called Ten For Today, which were records she was enjoying listening to in 1992.<ref>{{cite book |last=Blandford |first=James R. |year=2004 |title=PJ Harvey: Siren Rising |location=London |publisher=Omnibus Press |isbn=1-84449-433-0 |page=37}}</ref> [[Bob Nastanovich]] of [[Pavement (band)|Pavement]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Jovanovic |first=Rob |year=2004 |title=Perfect Sound Forever: The Story of Pavement |location=Boston |publisher=[[Justin, Charles & Co.]] |isbn=1-932112-07-3 |page=129}}</ref> and Mark Clifford of [[Seefeel]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.furious.com/perfect/staff2.html |title=Perfect Sound Forever\u2013 Interviewee's Favorite Music |work=furious.com |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> have also cited ''Spiderland'' as among their favorite albums. The album cover of ''Spiderland'' was recreated by [[The Shins]] in the music video for \"[[New Slang]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dallasobserver.com/2002-07-11/music/the-shins/ |title=The Shins \u2013 Page 1 \u2013 Music \u2013 Dallas \u2013 ''Dallas Observer'' |last=Mercer |first=Ben |date=July 11, 2002 |work=[[Dallas Observer|dallasobserver.com]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Reunions ===\n[[Image:Spiderland advert.JPG|thumb|An advertisement for Slint's performance of ''Spiderland'' at the 2007 Pitchfork Music Festival]]\nDespite having plans for a tour of Europe to promote ''Spiderland'', Slint broke up in November 1990, after Brian McMahan decided to quit the band.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bangs|first1=Lance|title=Breadcrumb Trail|date=November 3, 2014}}</ref> Members of the band went on to join other musical projects, including [[Tortoise (band)|Tortoise]], [[The Breeders]], [[Will Oldham|Palace]] and [[The For Carnation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/slint-mn0000751604 |title=Slint \u2013 Music Biography, Credits and Discography: AllMusic |last=Ankeny |first=Jason |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> Slint reunited briefly in 2005 for an eighteen-date tour. Pajo said, \"We don't want to be a reunion band that keeps reuniting.&nbsp;... I know that this is going to be it.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Harrington |first=Richard |date=March 18, 2005 |title='Post-Rock' Slint Briefly Reunites |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=http://www.staugustine.com/stories/032505/com_2970671.shtml |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206064103/http://www.staugustine.com/stories/032505/com_2970671.shtml |archivedate=February 6, 2012 }}</ref> However, in 2007 Slint reunited again for a tour featuring performances of ''Spiderland'' in its entirety as part of [[All Tomorrow's Parties (music festival)|All Tomorrow's Parties]]' \"[[Don't Look Back (concert series)|Don't Look Back]]\" concert series celebrating classic albums.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/nme/27283 |title=Slint Announce More Performances of <nowiki>'</nowiki>''Spiderland''<nowiki>'</nowiki> <nowiki>| News |</nowiki> nme.com |date=March 23, 2007 |work=[[NME|nme.com]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006132822/http://www.nme.com/news/nme/27283 |archive-date=October 6, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The tour included appearances at the 2007 [[Pitchfork Music Festival]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Solarski |first=Matthew |title=Slint Join Sonic Youth for Pitchfork Fest Kickoff |url=http://pitchfork.com/article/news/42492-gza-slint-join-sonic-youth-for-pitchfork-fest-kickoff |date=April 20, 2007 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and [[Primavera Sound Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Solarski |first=Matthew |title=Slint Rock ''Spiderland'' at Primavera Sound Festival |url=http://pitchfork.com/article/news/40491-slint-rock-ispiderlandi-at-primavera-sound-festival |date=January 16, 2007 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> McMahan said in an interview at the Pitchfork Music Festival that performing the album live was \"pretty cool. It moves a little slower than it does on the record, but it's all there.&nbsp;... It took some getting used to, some revisiting the material and rehearsing.\"<ref name=\"2007 pfork fest friday\">{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=Paul |title=Interview: Brian McMahan of Slint |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=July 13, 2007 |url=http://pitchfork.com/article/feature/44244-pitchfork-music-festival-2007-friday |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20090318022157/http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6649-pitchfork-music-festival-2007-friday/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 18, 2009 }}</ref> In an August 2013 interview with [[Vish Khanna]], former producer [[Steve Albini]] revealed that the band was working on remastering ''Spiderland'' with engineer [[Bob Weston]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://vishkhanna.com/2013/08/16/ep-24-steve-albini/ |title=Ep. #24: Steve Albini &#124; Kreative Kontrol |publisher=Vishkhanna.com |date=August 16, 2013 |accessdate=June 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nCritical responses to Slint's reunion have been mixed, with detractors commenting on the music's unsuitability for a live setting. ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' music critic [[Jim DeRogatis]] wrote that although \"fans greeted [Slint's performance at the Pitchfork Music Festival] as manna from heaven.&nbsp;[...] the musicians' fragile, intertwining guitar lines, mumbled attempts at poetry and uninspiring [[shoegazing|shoegazer]] personas were poor matches for the setting and the occasion, especially during the static, percussion-deprived 'Don, Aman' and the bloated anthem 'Good Morning, Captain'.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=DeRogatis |first=Jim |authorlink=Jim DeRogatis |title=Pitchfork Music Fest Diary and Features |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=July 15, 2007}}</ref> According to members of [[The A.V. Club]], Slint's performance of \"Don, Aman\" at the festival \"capture[d] the band's greatness ''and'' its greatest weakness: Slint completely lacks stage charisma, and playing a deathly quiet, moody song on a big outdoor stage just doesn't work.\"<ref name=\"AV\">{{cite web |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/festival-diary-the-2007-pitchfork-music-festival,1998/ |title=Festival Diary: The 2007 Pitchfork Music Festival <nowiki>| Music |</nowiki> The A.V. Club |last1=Gordon |first1=Scott |last2=Modell |first2=Josh |last3=O'Neal |first3=Sean |last4=Ryan |first4=Kyle |date=July 18, 2007 |work=[[The A.V. Club|avclub.com]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> Both DeRogatis and the ''A. V. Club'' review also noted that the band's performance was plagued by sound problems.<ref name=\"AV\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=DeRogatis |first=Jim |authorlink=Jim DeRogatis |date=July 16, 2007 |title=Indie Oasis |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |url=http://www.jimdero.com/News2007/Pitchforkroundup.htm |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> A ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' review of a performance at [[Webster Hall]] opined \"the deeply brooding, fussily-executed album finally sounded, sixteen years later, like the existential, cosmos-annihilating shrug it was envisioned as. Which is to say: It sounded fucking great.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2007/07/slint_plays_a_funeral_mass_for.html |title=Slint Plays a Funeral Mass for the Album \u2013 Vulture |last=Catucci |first=Nick |date=July 18, 2007 |work=vulture.com |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Remastered box set==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Spiderland <small>(remastered)</small>\n| type       = Box set\n| artist     = [[Slint]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|4|15|mf=yes}}\n| recorded   = 1989\u20131992\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flat list|\n*[[Post-rock]]}}\n| length     = {{Duration|h=1|m=58|s=35}} <small>+ [[Breadcrumb Trail (film)|DVD]]</small>\n| label      = [[Touch and Go Records|Touch and Go]]\n| producer   = [[Brian Paulson]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nIn 2014, Touch and Go reissued ''[[Tweez]]'' and a version of ''Spiderland'' remastered by [[Bob Weston]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.avclub.com/slint-s-spiderland-box-rewards-patient-listeners-patie-1798180170|title=Slint\u2019s Spiderland box rewards patient listeners, patient fans|website=Music}}</ref> On April 15, a deluxe box set was released containing the remastered ''Spiderland'' album, fourteen previously unreleased tracks, the DVD documentary ''[[Breadcrumb Trail (film)|Breadcrumb Trail]]'', and a photobook documenting Slint's history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://touchandgorecords.com/bands/album.php?id=499|title=Spiderland (remastered) Box Set &#124; Slint &#124; Touch and Go / Quarterstick Records|website=touchandgorecords.com}}</ref> All 3,138 hand-numbered copies sold out prior to release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.touchandgorecords.com/products/slint-spiderland-remastered|title=Slint Spiderland (remastered)|website=Touch And Go Records}}</ref>\n\nThe bonus tracks featured in the set were selected by Slint and include demos, outtakes, and a live performance. The songs \"Pam\" and \"Glen\" (a reinterpretation of the original) were recorded during the ''Spiderland'' sessions and failed to make the album.<ref>Minskor, Evan. \"[http://pitchfork.com/news/53769-slints-spiderland-gets-deluxe-box-set-reissue/ Slint's Spiderland Gets Deluxe Box Set Reissue]\", January 30, 2014. Retrieved on May 15, 2017.</ref> \"Todd's Song\" and \"Brian's Song\" were recorded after ''Spiderland'' while the band was briefly reformed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/Slint-todds-song-lyrics|title=Slint \u2013 Todd's Song|via=genius.com}}</ref> \"Cortez the Killer\", a cover of the [[Neil Young]] [[Cortez the Killer|song by the same name]], was recorded on March 3, 1989, during a live performance in [[Chicago]]. Demos of \"Nosferatu Man\", \"Washer\", and \"Good Morning, Captain\" were also selected for the release.\n\nRemnants of the second \"bonus tracks\" disc (sides E/F) from the ''Spiderland'' box set were sold separately in plastic sleeves from Touch and Go's website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426141127/http://store.touchandgorecords.com/collections/frontpage/products/slint-spiderland-remastered-vinyl-lp-of-bonus-sides-e-f-only|title=Slint Spiderland (remastered) Vinyl LP Of Bonus Tracks Sides E/F \u2013 Touch And Go Records|date=April 26, 2016|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> The disc \u2013 one of two bonus LPs from the collection \u2013 contains eight of the set's fourteen previously unreleased tracks.\n\n== Track listing ==\nAll songs written by Todd Brashear, [[Brian McMahan]], [[David Pajo]], and [[Britt Walford]], except where noted.\n{{Track listing \n|title1=Breadcrumb Trail\n|length1=5:55\n|title2=Nosferatu Man\n|length2=5:35\n|title3=Don, Aman\n|length3=6:28\n|title4=Washer\n|length4=8:50\n|title5=For Dinner...\n|length5=5:05\n|title6=Good Morning, Captain\n|length6=7:38\n|writer3 = McMahan, Pajo, Walford}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = 2014 Deluxe Remastered Version\n| title1=Breadcrumb Trail|note1=Remastered\n| length1=5:54\n| title2=Nosferatu Man |note2=Remastered\n| length2=5:34\n| title3=Don, Aman |note3=Remastered\n| length3=6:27\n| title4=Washer |note4=Remastered\n| length4=8:49\n| title5=For Dinner... |note5=Remastered\n| length5=5:05\n| title6=Good Morning, Captain |note6=Remastered\n| length6=7:41\n| title7=Nosferatu Man |note7=Basement practice\n| length7=7:05\n| title8=Washer |note8=Basement practice\n| length8=4:48\n| title9=Good Morning, Captain |note9=[[Demo (music)|Demo]]\n| length9=7:34\n| title10=Pam |note10=Rough [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mix]] of ''Spiderland'' [[outtake]]\n| length10=4:44\n| title11=Glenn |note11=''Spiderland'' outtake\n| length11=7:59\n| title12=Todd's Song |note12=Post-''Spiderland'' song in progress\n| length12=7:22\n| title13=Brian's Song |note13=Post-''Spiderland'' demo\n| length13=5:57\n| title14=[[Cortez the Killer]] |note14=Live in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], March 3, 1989\n| length14=8:36\n| title15=Washer |note15=[[Multitrack recording|4-track]] vocal demo\n| length15=7:21\n| title16=Nosferatu Man |note16=4-track vocal demo\n| length16=5:23\n| title17=Pam |note17=4-track vocal demo\n| length17=3:33\n| title18=Good Morning, Captain |note18=Evanston Riff tape\n| length18=0:45\n| title19=Nosferatu Man |note19=Evanston Riff tape\n| length19=3:18\n| title20=Pam |note20=Evanston Riff tape\n| length20=4:39\n|writer14 = [[Neil Young]]}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = iTunes Bonus Tracks\n| title7          = Utica Quarry, Nighttime\n| length7         = 15:38\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n;Slint\n* Todd Brashear&nbsp;\u2013 [[bass guitar]]\n* [[David Pajo]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[guitar]]\n* [[Brian McMahan]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar, [[Singing|vocals]]\n* [[Britt Walford]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]], vocals, guitar on \"Don, Aman\"\n\n;Technical personnel\n* [[Will Oldham]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Cover art|photography]]\n* [[Brian Paulson]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[audio engineer|engineering]]\n* Noel Saltzman&nbsp;\u2013 photography\n\n== Accolades ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Country\n! Accolade\n! Year\n! Rank\n|-\n| ''[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]''\n| United States\n| The 90 Greatest Albums of the 90s\n| 1998\n| 34<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/apress.html |title=Rocklist.net..''Alternative Press''.. |work=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| US\n| Top 100 Albums of the 1990s\n| 1999\n| 12<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/5923-top-100-albums-of-the-1990s/9/ |title=Staff Lists: Top 100 Albums of the 1990s <nowiki>| Features |</nowiki> Pitchfork |date=November 17, 2003 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Melody Maker]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| All Time Top 100 Albums\n| 2000\n| 55<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/maker100.htm |title=Rocklist.net...''Melody Maker'' Top 100 Albums \u2013 2000 ..... |work=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[NME]]''\n| UK\n| 100 Best Albums\n| 2003\n| 53<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/nmes_100_best_albums.htm |title=Rocklist.net...''NME'' Writers Lists... |work=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| US\n| 100 Greatest Albums, 1985\u20132005\n| 2005\n| 94<ref name=\"Spin 100\" />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Discogs master|38099|type=album}}\n*{{Musicbrainz release group|e9f4b96a-94df-36be-9659-c9a811caead6}}\n{{Featured article}}\n\n{{Slint}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:1991 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Brian Paulson]]\n[[Category:Slint albums]]\n[[Category:Touch and Go Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Album}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Spiderland\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Slint]]\n| cover      = Slint - Spiderland.jpg\n| alt        = A black-and-white photograph of Slint standing in tall water with only part of their faces visible\n| released   = {{Start date|1991|3|27|mf=yes}}\n| recorded   = August\u2013October 1990\n| venue      =\n| studio     = {{ubl|[[River North Records]]|{{small|([[Chicago]], [[Illinois]])}}}}\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Post-rock]]\n* [[math rock]]\n* [[post-hardcore]]\n}}\n| length     = {{Duration|m=39|s=31}}\n| label      = [[Touch and Go Records|Touch and Go]]\n| producer   = [[Brian Paulson]]\n| prev_title = [[Tweez]]\n| prev_year  = 1989\n| next_title = [[Untitled Slint EP|Untitled]]\n| next_year  = 1994\n}}\n'''''Spiderland''''' is the second and final studio album by the American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Slint]]. It was released on March 27, 1991, through [[Touch and Go Records]]. Featuring dramatically alternating [[Dynamics (music)|dynamics]] and vocals ranging from [[spoken word]] to shouting, the album contains [[narrative]] lyrics that emphasize alienation. ''Spiderland'' was Slint's first release on Touch and Go, and the group's only album to feature Todd Brashear.\n\nAlthough ''Spiderland'' was not widely recognized on its initial release, it eventually sold more than 50,000 copies and became a landmark album in [[underground music]] after Slint broke up. The album has been influential on the styles of many bands in the [[post-rock]] genres. In 2005, 2007 and 2013\u20132014, Slint reunited for a tour consisting of performances of ''Spiderland'' in its entirety.\n\n== Background ==\n\nSlint formed in 1986 in [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], [[Kentucky]], from the remnants of the [[punk rock]] band [[Squirrel Bait]]; the founding members included [[Brian McMahan]] (guitar, vocals), [[David Pajo]] (guitar), [[Britt Walford]] (drums) and [[Ethan Buckler]] (bass guitar). The band's debut album, the [[Steve Albini]]-produced ''[[Tweez]]'', was released on the group's self-owned [[Record label|label]] Jennifer Hartman Records and Tapes.<ref name=\"T&G bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.touchandgorecords.com/bands/band.php?id=70 |title=Slint <nowiki>|</nowiki> Touch and Go / Quarterstick Records |work=touchandgorecords.com |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref> The album's sound has been described as a combination of \"scratchy guitars, thumping bass lines and hard hitting drums\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sputnikmusic.com/review/6290/Slint-Tweez/ |title=Slint \u2013 ''Tweez'' (Album Review) <nowiki>|</nowiki> Sputnikmusic |last=Jackson |first=Chris |date=April 16, 2006 |work=[[Sputnikmusic]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref> Buckler promptly left the band out of dissatisfaction with Albini's production, and was replaced with Todd Brashear.<ref name=\"musicianguide\" /> The band's second recording was for the [[instrumental]] [[extended play]] ''[[Slint (EP)|Slint]]'', which included a new version of \"Rhoda\" from ''Tweez''. The EP, which would not be released until 1994, was a departure from ''Tweez''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s sound and reflected the band's new musical direction.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.southern.com/southern/band/SLINT/biog.html |title=Slint |work=[[Southern Records|southern.com]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090716153944/http://www.southern.com/southern/band/SLINT/biog.html |archivedate=July 16, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nAfter the band ended its brief tour in support of ''Tweez'', most of its members attended college.<ref name=\"musicianguide\" /> Around this time McMahan and Walford began writing together for the band's next record, creating six new songs which the band practiced throughout the summer of 1990.<ref name=\"musicianguide\" /> Slint entered River North Records in August 1990 to record ''Spiderland''. At that time there were no vocals or lyrics prepared for the album, so the band wrote them while in the studio.<ref name=\"musicianguide\" /> The album's producer, [[Brian Paulson]], was known for his \"live\" recording style in the studio, with minimal [[take]]s.<ref name=\"indyweek\">{{cite web |url=http://www.indyweek.com/gyrobase/Content?oid=oid%3A23657 |title=''Independent Weekly'': Special Issues: Rock & Roll Quarterly: Brian Paulson |last=Parker |first=Chris |date=February 9, 2005 |work=[[Independent Weekly|indyweek.com]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330130145/https://www.indyweek.com/indyweek/brian-paulson/Content?oid=1194172 |archive-date=2018-03-30 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Paulson recalled \"It was weird while I was doing [''Spiderland''] because I remember sitting there, and I just knew there was something about it. I've never heard anything like this. I'm really digging this but it's really fucking weird.\"<ref name=\"indyweek\" />\n\nThe recording sessions for ''Spiderland'' are reputed to have been difficult for the members of the band and were, according to [[AllMusic]], \"intense, traumatic and one more piece of evidence supporting the theory that band members had to be periodically [[Institutionalisation|institutionalized]] during the completion of the album.\"<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/spiderland-mw0000267497 |title=''Spiderland'' \u2013 Slint : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards : AllMusic |last=Carlson |first=Dean |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616180251/http://www.allmusic.com/album/spiderland-mw0000267497 |archivedate=June 16, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Rumors circulated that at least one member of Slint had been checked into a [[psychiatric hospital]].<ref name=\"p. 640\" /> Walford later addressed these stories in an article in ''[[Select (magazine)|Select]]'' by saying, \"[We were] definitely trying to be serious about things, pretty intense, which made recording the album kinda stressful.\"<ref name=\"p. 640\" /> The recording was completed in four days.<ref name=\"indyweek\" />\n\n== Music ==\n\n{{Listen\n |filename = Breadcrumb Trail - Slint.ogg\n |title = \"Breadcrumb Trail\"\n |description = A sample of \"Breadcrumb Trail\", the [[opening track]] from Slint's 1991 album, ''Spiderland''. This sample contains part of the song's verse, bridge, and chorus.\n |filename2 = Good Morning Captain - Slint.ogg\n |title2 = \"Good Morning, Captain\"\n |description2 = A sample of \"Good Morning, Captain\", the sixth track from ''Spiderland''. This sample contains part of the song's second verse.\n}}\n\nThe music of ''Spiderland'' is noted for its angular guitar rhythms, dramatically alternating [[Dynamics (music)|dynamic]] shifts and irregular [[time signature]]s. McMahan's singing style interchanges between mumbling [[spoken word]] and strained shouting. The lyrics of ''Spiderland'' are often written in a [[narrative]] style. Influences on the record included [[Gang of Four (band)|Gang of Four]], [[Black Sabbath]] and [[Sonic Youth]].<ref name=\"Guardian Camber Sands Holiday Centre\" /> Will Hermes of ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' summarized the album's sound as \"mid-'70s [[King Crimson]] gone [[emo]]: screeching guitar chords and gorgeous note-spinning in odd-metered instrumentals speckled with words both spoken and sung\".<ref name=\"Spin 100\">{{cite journal |last=Hermes |first=Will |date=July 2005 |title=Slint \u2013 ''Spiderland'' |magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]}}</ref>\n\nThe album's opening track, \"Breadcrumb Trail\", describes a day spent at a carnival with a [[Fortune-telling|fortune-teller]].<ref name=\"Breadcrumb Trail\" /> The song features a complex arrangement with sharp transitions, and the guitar fluctuates between a clean-sounding [[riff]] with [[harmonic]]s in the [[Verse (music)|verse]] to heavy [[Distortion (guitar)|distortion]] featuring extremely high-pitched notes in the [[Song structure (popular music)#Chorus|chorus]].<ref name=\"Breadcrumb Trail\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/breadcrumb-trail-mt0008849294 |title=Breadcrumb Trail \u2013 Slint : Listen, Appearances, Song Review : AllMusic |last=Maginnis |first=Tom |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"Nosferatu Man\", the second track, is inspired by the 1922 [[German Expressionism|German Expressionist]] [[silent film]] ''[[Nosferatu]]''.<ref name=\"Nosferatu Man\" /> The song's verse includes a [[Consonance and dissonance|dissonant]] guitar riff, which uses high-pitched notes similar to those in \"Breadcrumb Trail\" and a drumbeat based on [[snare drum|snare]] and [[Tom-tom drum|toms]], absent of [[cymbal]]s.<ref name=\"Nosferatu Man\" /> The chorus, featuring \"jagged\" distorted guitar and a beat with \"thrashing cymbals with quick [[Fill (music)|drum fills]]\", segues into an extended [[Jam session|jam]] before the song ends with 30 seconds of [[Audio feedback|feedback]].<ref name=\"Nosferatu Man\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/nosferatu-man-mt0000860534 |title=Nosferatu Man \u2013 Slint : Listen, Appearances, Song Review : AllMusic |last=Maginnis |first=Tom |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"Don, Aman\" features Walford on lead vocals and guitar. Delivered in a hushed tone, the song's ambiguous lyrics depict the thoughts of an \"isolated soul\" before, after and during an evening at a bar.<ref name=\"Don, Aman\" /> The [[tempo]] quickens throughout, and then becomes loud and distorted before slowing back to the original tempo.<ref name=\"Don, Aman\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/don-aman-mt0000298526 |title=Don, Aman \u2013 Slint : Listen, Appearances, Song Review : AllMusic |last=Maginnis |first=Tom |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"Washer\", the album's longest track, features a \"barely audible\" intro with guitar and cymbals before the rest of the band comes in.<ref name=\"Washer\" /> The song builds tension until the final verse, which features loud distortion, and is followed by a lengthy [[Conclusion (music)|outro]].<ref name=\"Washer\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/washer-mt0004679278 |title=Washer \u2013 Slint : Listen, Appearances, Song Review : AllMusic |last=Maginnis |first=Tom |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"For Dinner...\" is an [[instrumental]] track.<ref name=\"For Dinner\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/for-dinner-mt0003956572 |title=For Dinner... \u2013 Slint : Listen, Appearances, Song Review : AllMusic |last=Maginnis |first=Tom |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref> Beginning with a quiet section of \"brooding chords throb[bing] with the occasional rumble of muted toms and bass drum\", the song cycles through sections of building and releasing tension.<ref name=\"For Dinner\" />\n\nThe final song of the album, \"Good Morning, Captain\", is a tribute to the [[Samuel Taylor Coleridge]] poem ''[[The Rime of the Ancient Mariner]]''.<ref name=\"Good Morning Captain\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/good-morning-captain-mt0001620569 |title=Good Morning Captain \u2013 Slint : Listen, Appearances, Song Review : AllMusic |last=Maginnis |first=Tom |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref> The song features a two chord guitar structure, a \"spindly, tight riff\" from the rhythm section and a \"jerky\" beat.<ref name=\"Good Morning Captain\" /> During the recording of the song's final chorus, McMahan became physically sick due to the strain of yelling over the guitars.<ref name=\"p. 640\" /> David Peschek of ''[[The Guardian]]'' compared \"Good Morning, Captain\" to [[Led Zeppelin]]'s \"[[Stairway to Heaven]]\", writing that \"the extraordinary Good Morning Captain is [Slint's] Stairway to Heaven, if it's possible to imagine Stairway to Heaven bleached of all bombast.\"<ref name=\"Guardian Camber Sands Holiday Centre\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/feb/28/popandrock.alltomorrowsparties |title=Slint, Camber Sands Holiday Centre <nowiki>| Music |</nowiki> ''The Guardian'' |last=Peschek |first=David |date=February 28, 2005 |work=[[The Guardian|guardian.co.uk]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn the iTunes edition of the album, an additional track is added to the end of the album, entitled \"Utica Quarry, Nighttime\". The track is, simply, 15 minutes of field recordings of Utica Quarry, the same place where the photos for Spiderland were taken.\n\n== Title and packaging ==\n\n[[Image:Slint - Spiderland promo.JPG|thumb|Slint in a photo taken by [[Will Oldham]] from the same session as the ''Spiderland'' cover<ref name=\"Southern Gallery\">{{cite web |url=http://www.southern.com/southern/band/SLINT/gallery.html |title=Slint Gallery |work=[[Southern Records|southern.com]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090803222536/http://www.southern.com/southern/band/SLINT/gallery.html |archivedate=August 3, 2009 }}</ref>]]\n\nThe name ''Spiderland'' originates from McMahan's younger brother, who thought that the record sounded \"spidery\".<ref name=\"p. 640\" /> The album's [[black-and-white]] cover photograph, which depicts the members of the band (Brashear, McMahan, Walford and Pajo, from left to right) treading water in the lake of an abandoned quarry, was taken by [[Will Oldham]].<ref name=\"musicianguide\">{{cite web |url=http://www.musicianguide.com/biographies/1608004609/Slint.html |title=Slint Biography |last=McCarthy |first=Shannon |work=musicianguide.com |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> An article in ''[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]]'' credited the cover for creating a mystique surrounding Slint, noting \"[m]ost people only had seen Slint as four heads floating in a Kentucky quarry on Spiderland's cover. Listeners pondered the band's sparsely adorned black-and-white covers as if they were runes bearing secrets.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Segal |first=Dave |date=March 10, 2005 |title=Web of Influence |newspaper=[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]] |url=http://www.thestranger.com/seattle/Content?oid=20786 |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> Chris Gaerig of the ''[[Michigan Daily]]'' wrote, \"the cover of Slint's masterful ''Spiderland'' captures the joyous fear and violence of the album so precisely it shakes souls. The group\u2014submerged in a lake to their chins with deranged smiles\u2014seems to be stalking you, hovering out of the black-and-white fa\u00e7ade.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://media.www.michigandaily.com/media/storage/paper851/news/2007/09/20/TheBSide/Cover.Stories-2980669.shtml |title=Cover Stories \u2013 The B-Side |last=Gaerig |first=Chris |date=September 20, 2007 |work=[[Michigan Daily|michigandaily.com]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080220222104/http://media.www.michigandaily.com/media/storage/paper851/news/2007/09/20/TheBSide/Cover.Stories-2980669.shtml |archivedate=February 20, 2008 }}</ref> Several other promotional images have been taken from the same photo session with Oldham.<ref name=\"Southern Gallery\" />\n\nA photo of a [[spider]] taken by Noel Saltzman is used on the back cover, reflecting the album's title. The inside sleeve contains the message \"interested female vocalists write 1864 douglas blvd. louisville, ky. 40205\". McMahan confirmed that this message was serious, and said \"We did get some responses and we did listen to CDs and tapes. We didn't end up doing anything immediately, so that idea of adding someone sort of fell by the wayside.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Simigis |first=Antonia |date=July 12, 2007 |title=On the record: Slint |newspaper=Time Out Chicago}}</ref> The message \"this recording is meant to be listened to on vinyl\" is printed on some [[Compact Disc|CD]] issues of ''Spiderland'', demonstrating Slint's preference of [[analog signal|analog]] audio devices.<ref name=\"DLB\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dontlookbackconcerts.com/dlbarchive/dlb2007archive/slint/review |title=Don't Look Back \u2013 Don't Look Back 2007 \u2013 Slint \u2013 Review |work=don'tlookbackconcerts.com |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Critical reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1       = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score  = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic2\">{{cite web|last=Deming|first=Mark|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/spiderland-mw0000267497|title=''Spiderland'' \u2013 Slint : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards : AllMusic|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref>\n| rev2       = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2Score  = A<ref>{{cite web|last=Eakin|first=Marah|url=http://www.avclub.com/review/slints-spiderland-box-rewards-patient-listeners-pa-203207|title=Slint's Spiderland box rewards patient listeners, patient fans|website=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=April 15, 2014|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev3       = ''[[Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s|Christgau's Consumer Guide]]''\n| rev3Score  = C+<ref name=\"RCreview\"/>\n| rev4       = ''[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]''\n| rev4Score  = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|last=Larkin|first=Colin|authorlink=Colin Larkin (writer)|publisher=[[Omnibus Press]]|edition=5th concise|year=2011|isbn=0-85712-595-8}}</ref>\n| rev5       = ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]''\n| rev5Score  = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Male|first=Andrew|title=Slint: Spiderland|journal=[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]|issue=246|date=May 2014}}</ref>\n| rev6       = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| Rev6Score  = 10/10<ref name=\"p4k-reissue\">{{cite web|last=Berman|first=Stuart|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/19182-slint-spiderland-remastered-box-set/|title=Slint: Spiderland|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=April 16, 2014|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev7       = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev7Score  = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Slint: Spiderland|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|issue=334|date=May 2014|page=124}}</ref>\n| rev8       = ''[[Record Collector]]''\n| rev8Score  = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|last=Atkins|first=Jamie|url=http://recordcollectormag.com/reviews/spiderland|title=Slint \u2013 Spiderland|journal=[[Record Collector]]|issue=426|date=April 2014|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev9       = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev9Score  = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"RSguide\"/>\n| rev10      = ''[[Select (magazine)|Select]]''\n| rev10Score = 4/5<ref name=\"select\">{{cite journal|last=Noon|first=Mike|title=Slint: Spiderland|journal=[[Select (magazine)|Select]]|issue=8|date=February 1991|page=73}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Spiderland'' received widespread critical acclaim from [[music journalism|music critics]], including ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'', ''[[NME]]'', and ''[[The Village Voice]]''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FPmoAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=June 4, 2014|pages=27\u20138|title=Slint's Spiderland|last=Tennent|first=Scott|publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury Publishing USA]]|series=[[33\u2153]]|year=2010|isbn=1-4411-9014-7}}</ref> In a contemporary review for ''[[Melody Maker]]'', [[Steve Albini]], producer of Slint's 1989 album ''Tweez'', gave the album ten stars and called it \"a majestic album, sublime and strange, made more brilliant by its simplicity and quiet grace.\" Albini found its unadorned production impeccable and said that it vividly captures McMahan and Pajo's playing so well that their guitars \"seem to hover in space directly past the listener's nose\", while \"the incredibly precise-yet-instinctive drumming has the same range and wallop it would in your living room.\"<ref name=\"melodymaker\">{{cite journal |last=Albini |first=Steve |authorlink=Steve Albini |date=March 30, 1991 |title=<nowiki>[</nowiki>Steve Albini review<nowiki>]</nowiki> |magazine=[[Melody Maker]]}}</ref> ''[[Select (magazine)|Select]]'' noted that the band's popularity in the college circuit was \"probably due to the college circuit celebrity status of their drummer \u2013 Shannon Doughton, aka Britt Walford, the only male member of the 'all-female' indie supergroup [[The Breeders]]\".<ref name=\"select\" /> Their review noted the multiple listens it may take to appreciate it, acknowledging the album as \"immediate as a snail trail to hell, 'Spiderland' needs several plays to burn its way into your consciousness, but when it does...\"<ref name=\"select\" />\n\nIn a retrospective review for [[AllMusic]], Mark Deming said that ''Spiderland'' is \"one of the most important indie albums of the '90s\" and a \"singular achievement\" which found the band \"working with dynamics that made the silences every bit as much presence as the guitars and drums, manipulating space and time as they stretched out and juggled time signatures, and conjuring melodies that were as sparse and fragmented as they were beautiful\".<ref name=\"AllMusic2\"/> [[Robert Christgau]] was less enthusiastic and wrote that, despite their \"sad-sack affect\", Slint are actually \"[[Art rock|art-rockers]] without the courage of their pretensions\" with poor lyrics.<ref name=\"RCreview\">{{cite book|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|year=2000|page=285|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xVQbszFuEGMC&pg=PA285&lpg=PA285#v=onepage&q&f=false|chapter=Slint: Spiderland|title=[[Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s]]|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]|isbn=0-312-24560-2|accessdate=June 9, 2014}}</ref> In ''[[The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]]'', ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' journalist Mac Randall felt that the album's music lacks songform, even though it sounds more accessible than ''Tweez'': \"[t]he absence of anything resembling a tune continues to nag.\"<ref name=\"RSguide\">{{cite book |last=Randall |first=Mac |chapter=Slint |editor-last1=Brackett |editor-first1=Nathan |editor-last2=Hoard |editor-first2=Christian |year=2004 |title=[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide|The New Rolling Stone Album Guide]] |location=New York |edition=4th |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |isbn=0-7432-0169-8 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/744 744\u2013745] }}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]'' wrote of ''Spiderland'': \"a heady, chilling listen; the irregularity of its hypnotic melodies, fractured beats and mismatched lyrics demand a new kind of appreciation, independent of traditional notions of songcraft. With its half-mumbled, half-hollered vocals, deliberate percussion and drone-gone-aggressive guitars, ''Spiderland''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s urgency is almost traumatic to swallow: despondency never tasted so real.\" They named it the twelfth best album of the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/5923-top-100-albums-of-the-1990s/9/ |title=Staff Lists: Top 100 Albums of the 1990s <nowiki>| Features |</nowiki> Pitchfork |date=November 17, 2003 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> In 2014, ''Spiderland'' was [[reissue]]d as a [[box set]], featuring 14 previously unreleased tracks, and received widespread critical acclaim; it holds an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 99 out of 100 at [[Metacritic]], based on 11 reviews from mainstream publications.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/spiderland-box-set/slint |title=Reviews for Spiderland [Box Set&#93; by Slint |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=June 25, 2014}}</ref> In 2015, ''[[Gigwise]]'' named the album in their list \"The 11 most vicious [[post-hardcore]] albums ever\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gigwise.com/photos/104217/welcome-back-glassjaw:-the-11-most-vicious-post-hardcore-albums-ever|title=Welcome back Glassjaw: The 11 most vicious post-hardcore albums ever|last=Butler|first=Will|date=December 2, 2015|website=[[Gigwise]]|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n== Legacy ==\n[[Image:Slint at Pitchfork Music Festival.jpg|thumb|Slint performing ''Spiderland'' at the 2007 [[Pitchfork Music Festival]]]]\nThough largely ignored upon its initial release, ''Spiderland'' has attracted greater attention through time. The album has sold over 50,000 copies,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sfj.abstractdynamics.org/archives/006014.html |title=S/FJ: You Thought I Was Backing Out |date=July 25, 2005 |work=abstractdynamics.org |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> though Kory Grow of the ''[[College Music Journal]]'' suggested that the album \"has inspired countless bands (and therefore fans) far beyond its [[Nielsen SoundScan|SoundScan]] numbers\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Grow |first=Kory |date=July 19, 2007 |title=Review: Slint Performs Spiderland in New York |magazine=[[College Music Journal]]}}</ref> ''Spiderland'' has become a landmark indie rock album and is considered, along with [[Talk Talk]]'s ''[[Spirit of Eden]]'' and ''[[Laughing Stock (album)|Laughing Stock]]'', to have been the primary catalyst of the [[post-rock]] genre.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/style/post-rock-ma0000002790 |title=Post-Rock : Significant Albums, Artists and Songs, Most Viewed : AllMusic |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://altmusic.about.com/od/genres/a/post-rock.htm |title=Genre Profile \u2013 Post-Rock |last=Carew |first=Andrew |work=[[About.com]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121118155024/http://altmusic.about.com/od/genres/a/post-rock.htm |archivedate=November 18, 2012 }}</ref> The album is also regarded as being essential to \"the fabric of [[math-rock]] genre\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://drownedinsound.com/in_depth/3205162-math-rock-family-tree--exploring-the-roots-of-foals | title=Math-Rock Family Tree: exploring the roots of Foals | publisher=[[Drowned in Sound]] | date=April 24, 2008 | accessdate=August 13, 2015 | author=Diver, Mike}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theskinny.co.uk/music/news/slints-spiderland-to-get-deluxe-box-set-reissue | title=Slint's 'Spiderland' to get deluxe box-set reissue | work=[[The Skinny (magazine)|The Skinny]] | date=January 14, 2014 | accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref> David Peschek said that the album is \"the ur-text for what became known as post-rock, a fractured, almost geometric reimagining of rock music stripped of its dionysiac impulse.\"<ref name=\"Guardian Camber Sands Holiday Centre\"/> Rachel Devine of ''[[The List (magazine)|The List]]'' called ''Spiderland'' \"arguably the most disproportionately influential [album] in music history\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.list.co.uk/article/4190-90s-revival/ |title=90s Revival \u2013 Back for Good <nowiki>|</nowiki> ''The List'' |last=Devine |first=Rachel |date=August 16, 2007 |work=[[The List (magazine)|list.co.uk]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> ''Pitchfork'' reviewer Stuart Berman commented: \"''Spiderland''{{'}}s greatest legacy is not that it motivated a cluster of semi-popular bands in the late-90s and early 2000s to adopt its whisper-to-scream schematic. It's the boundless inspiration it perpetually provides for all the bands that have yet to emerge from the basement.\"<ref name=\"p4k-reissue\"/>\n\nMcMahan reflected on the album's success: \"We worked really hard on ''Spiderland''. I mean, I definitely felt much more personal about it. I thought it represented us as people, musically, a lot more than ''Tweez'' did. That's about it. It seemed like when we were around, and actively playing and stuff, that people's responses to us were fairly ambivalent. I thought it was funny when the press picked up on it. For an independent release, it had a strange sort of audience and kept selling three or four years after we recorded it; it still sells more copies than when it first came out.\"<ref>{{cite journal |last=Modell |first=Josh |date=April 1996 |title=The For Carnation |magazine=Milk |url=http://www.matadorrecords.com/bands/fc/milk.html |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418045221/http://matadorrecords.com/bands/fc/milk.html |archivedate=April 18, 2012 }}</ref> Touch and Go founder Corey Rusk said that ''Spiderland'' is \"like an icon now. But when it came out, nobody cared! The band had broken up by the time the album came out, and it really didn't sell particularly well or get written about all that much in the year it was released. But it was a revolutionary, groundbreaking record, and it's one of the few instances where people catch up to it later on.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/interviews/6419-corey-rusk/ |title=Interviews: Corey Rusk <nowiki>| Features |</nowiki> Pitchfork |last=Crock |first=Jason |date=September 5, 2006 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Spiderland'' has also been said by Michael Alan Goldberg to have been a considerable influence on post-rock bands [[Mogwai]], [[Godspeed You! Black Emperor]], [[Isis (band)|Isis]] and [[Explosions in the Sky]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Goldberg |first=Michael Alan |date=July 18, 2007 |title=The Last Time We Reunite (Except for That Next Time) |newspaper=[[SF Weekly]]}}</ref> [[Dinosaur Jr]] and [[Sebadoh]] member [[Lou Barlow]] said of ''Spiderland'', \"It was quiet-to-loud without sounding like [[grunge]] or indie rock. It sounded more like a new kind of music.\"<ref name=\"p. 640\">{{cite book |last=Irvin |first=Jim |year=2001 |title=The Mojo Collection: The Greatest Albums of All Time |location=Edinburgh |publisher=Mojo Books |isbn=1-84195-067-X |page=640}}</ref> [[PJ Harvey]] has included ''Spiderland'' in a list called Ten For Today, which were records she was enjoying listening to in 1992.<ref>{{cite book |last=Blandford |first=James R. |year=2004 |title=PJ Harvey: Siren Rising |location=London |publisher=Omnibus Press |isbn=1-84449-433-0 |page=37}}</ref> [[Bob Nastanovich]] of [[Pavement (band)|Pavement]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Jovanovic |first=Rob |year=2004 |title=Perfect Sound Forever: The Story of Pavement |location=Boston |publisher=[[Justin, Charles & Co.]] |isbn=1-932112-07-3 |page=129}}</ref> and Mark Clifford of [[Seefeel]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.furious.com/perfect/staff2.html |title=Perfect Sound Forever\u2013 Interviewee's Favorite Music |work=furious.com |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> have also cited ''Spiderland'' as among their favorite albums. The album cover of ''Spiderland'' was recreated by [[The Shins]] in the music video for \"[[New Slang]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dallasobserver.com/2002-07-11/music/the-shins/ |title=The Shins \u2013 Page 1 \u2013 Music \u2013 Dallas \u2013 ''Dallas Observer'' |last=Mercer |first=Ben |date=July 11, 2002 |work=[[Dallas Observer|dallasobserver.com]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Reunions ===\n[[Image:Spiderland advert.JPG|thumb|An advertisement for Slint's performance of ''Spiderland'' at the 2007 Pitchfork Music Festival]]\nDespite having plans for a tour of Europe to promote ''Spiderland'', Slint broke up in November 1990, after Brian McMahan decided to quit the band.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bangs|first1=Lance|title=Breadcrumb Trail|date=November 3, 2014}}</ref> Members of the band went on to join other musical projects, including [[Tortoise (band)|Tortoise]], [[The Breeders]], [[Will Oldham|Palace]] and [[The For Carnation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/slint-mn0000751604 |title=Slint \u2013 Music Biography, Credits and Discography: AllMusic |last=Ankeny |first=Jason |work=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> Slint reunited briefly in 2005 for an eighteen-date tour. Pajo said, \"We don't want to be a reunion band that keeps reuniting.&nbsp;... I know that this is going to be it.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Harrington |first=Richard |date=March 18, 2005 |title='Post-Rock' Slint Briefly Reunites |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=http://www.staugustine.com/stories/032505/com_2970671.shtml |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206064103/http://www.staugustine.com/stories/032505/com_2970671.shtml |archivedate=February 6, 2012 }}</ref> However, in 2007 Slint reunited again for a tour featuring performances of ''Spiderland'' in its entirety as part of [[All Tomorrow's Parties (music festival)|All Tomorrow's Parties]]' \"[[Don't Look Back (concert series)|Don't Look Back]]\" concert series celebrating classic albums.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nme.com/news/nme/27283 |title=Slint Announce More Performances of <nowiki>'</nowiki>''Spiderland''<nowiki>'</nowiki> <nowiki>| News |</nowiki> nme.com |date=March 23, 2007 |work=[[NME|nme.com]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006132822/http://www.nme.com/news/nme/27283 |archive-date=October 6, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The tour included appearances at the 2007 [[Pitchfork Music Festival]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Solarski |first=Matthew |title=Slint Join Sonic Youth for Pitchfork Fest Kickoff |url=http://pitchfork.com/article/news/42492-gza-slint-join-sonic-youth-for-pitchfork-fest-kickoff |date=April 20, 2007 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and [[Primavera Sound Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Solarski |first=Matthew |title=Slint Rock ''Spiderland'' at Primavera Sound Festival |url=http://pitchfork.com/article/news/40491-slint-rock-ispiderlandi-at-primavera-sound-festival |date=January 16, 2007 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> McMahan said in an interview at the Pitchfork Music Festival that performing the album live was \"pretty cool. It moves a little slower than it does on the record, but it's all there.&nbsp;... It took some getting used to, some revisiting the material and rehearsing.\"<ref name=\"2007 pfork fest friday\">{{cite web |last=Thompson |first=Paul |title=Interview: Brian McMahan of Slint |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=July 13, 2007 |url=http://pitchfork.com/article/feature/44244-pitchfork-music-festival-2007-friday |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20090318022157/http://pitchfork.com/features/articles/6649-pitchfork-music-festival-2007-friday/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=March 18, 2009 }}</ref> In an August 2013 interview with [[Vish Khanna]], former producer [[Steve Albini]] revealed that the band was working on remastering ''Spiderland'' with engineer [[Bob Weston]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://vishkhanna.com/2013/08/16/ep-24-steve-albini/ |title=Ep. #24: Steve Albini &#124; Kreative Kontrol |publisher=Vishkhanna.com |date=August 16, 2013 |accessdate=June 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nCritical responses to Slint's reunion have been mixed, with detractors commenting on the music's unsuitability for a live setting. ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' music critic [[Jim DeRogatis]] wrote that although \"fans greeted [Slint's performance at the Pitchfork Music Festival] as manna from heaven.&nbsp;[...] the musicians' fragile, intertwining guitar lines, mumbled attempts at poetry and uninspiring [[shoegazing|shoegazer]] personas were poor matches for the setting and the occasion, especially during the static, percussion-deprived 'Don, Aman' and the bloated anthem 'Good Morning, Captain'.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=DeRogatis |first=Jim |authorlink=Jim DeRogatis |title=Pitchfork Music Fest Diary and Features |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date=July 15, 2007}}</ref> According to members of [[The A.V. Club]], Slint's performance of \"Don, Aman\" at the festival \"capture[d] the band's greatness ''and'' its greatest weakness: Slint completely lacks stage charisma, and playing a deathly quiet, moody song on a big outdoor stage just doesn't work.\"<ref name=\"AV\">{{cite web |url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/festival-diary-the-2007-pitchfork-music-festival,1998/ |title=Festival Diary: The 2007 Pitchfork Music Festival <nowiki>| Music |</nowiki> The A.V. Club |last1=Gordon |first1=Scott |last2=Modell |first2=Josh |last3=O'Neal |first3=Sean |last4=Ryan |first4=Kyle |date=July 18, 2007 |work=[[The A.V. Club|avclub.com]] |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> Both DeRogatis and the ''A. V. Club'' review also noted that the band's performance was plagued by sound problems.<ref name=\"AV\" /><ref>{{cite news |last=DeRogatis |first=Jim |authorlink=Jim DeRogatis |date=July 16, 2007 |title=Indie Oasis |newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]] |url=http://www.jimdero.com/News2007/Pitchforkroundup.htm |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> A ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' review of a performance at [[Webster Hall]] opined \"the deeply brooding, fussily-executed album finally sounded, sixteen years later, like the existential, cosmos-annihilating shrug it was envisioned as. Which is to say: It sounded fucking great.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vulture.com/2007/07/slint_plays_a_funeral_mass_for.html |title=Slint Plays a Funeral Mass for the Album \u2013 Vulture |last=Catucci |first=Nick |date=July 18, 2007 |work=vulture.com |accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Remastered box set==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Spiderland <small>(remastered)</small>\n| type       = Box set\n| artist     = [[Slint]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|4|15|mf=yes}}\n| recorded   = 1989\u20131992\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flat list|\n*[[Post-rock]]}}\n| length     = {{Duration|h=1|m=58|s=35}} <small>+ [[Breadcrumb Trail (film)|DVD]]</small>\n| label      = [[Touch and Go Records|Touch and Go]]\n| producer   = [[Brian Paulson]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n}}\nIn 2014, Touch and Go reissued ''[[Tweez]]'' and a version of ''Spiderland'' remastered by [[Bob Weston]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://music.avclub.com/slint-s-spiderland-box-rewards-patient-listeners-patie-1798180170|title=Slint\u2019s Spiderland box rewards patient listeners, patient fans|website=Music}}</ref> On April 15, a deluxe box set was released containing the remastered ''Spiderland'' album, fourteen previously unreleased tracks, the DVD documentary ''[[Breadcrumb Trail (film)|Breadcrumb Trail]]'', and a photobook documenting Slint's history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://touchandgorecords.com/bands/album.php?id=499|title=Spiderland (remastered) Box Set &#124; Slint &#124; Touch and Go / Quarterstick Records|website=touchandgorecords.com}}</ref> All 3,138 hand-numbered copies sold out prior to release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://store.touchandgorecords.com/products/slint-spiderland-remastered|title=Slint Spiderland (remastered)|website=Touch And Go Records}}</ref>\n\nThe bonus tracks featured in the set were selected by Slint and include demos, outtakes, and a live performance. The songs \"Pam\" and \"Glen\" (a reinterpretation of the original) were recorded during the ''Spiderland'' sessions and failed to make the album.<ref>Minskor, Evan. \"[http://pitchfork.com/news/53769-slints-spiderland-gets-deluxe-box-set-reissue/ Slint's Spiderland Gets Deluxe Box Set Reissue]\", January 30, 2014. Retrieved on May 15, 2017.</ref> \"Todd's Song\" and \"Brian's Song\" were recorded after ''Spiderland'' while the band was briefly reformed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/Slint-todds-song-lyrics|title=Slint \u2013 Todd's Song|via=genius.com}}</ref> \"Cortez the Killer\", a cover of the [[Neil Young]] [[Cortez the Killer|song by the same name]], was recorded on March 3, 1989, during a live performance in [[Chicago]]. Demos of \"Nosferatu Man\", \"Washer\", and \"Good Morning, Captain\" were also selected for the release.\n\nRemnants of the second \"bonus tracks\" disc (sides E/F) from the ''Spiderland'' box set were sold separately in plastic sleeves from Touch and Go's website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426141127/http://store.touchandgorecords.com/collections/frontpage/products/slint-spiderland-remastered-vinyl-lp-of-bonus-sides-e-f-only|title=Slint Spiderland (remastered) Vinyl LP Of Bonus Tracks Sides E/F \u2013 Touch And Go Records|date=April 26, 2016|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> The disc \u2013 one of two bonus LPs from the collection \u2013 contains eight of the set's fourteen previously unreleased tracks.\n\n== Track listing ==\nAll songs written by Todd Brashear, [[Brian McMahan]], [[David Pajo]], and [[Britt Walford]], except where noted.\n{{Track listing \n|title1=Breadcrumb Trail\n|length1=5:55\n|title2=Nosferatu Man\n|length2=5:35\n|title3=Don, Aman\n|length3=6:28\n|title4=Washer\n|length4=8:50\n|title5=For Dinner...\n|length5=5:05\n|title6=Good Morning, Captain\n|length6=7:38\n|writer3 = McMahan, Pajo, Walford}}\n{{Track listing\n| headline        = 2014 Deluxe Remastered Version\n| title1=Breadcrumb Trail|note1=Remastered\n| length1=5:54\n| title2=Nosferatu Man |note