try\n! Accolade\n! Year\n! Rank\n|-\n| ''[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]''\n| United States\n| The 90 Greatest Albums of the 90s\n| 1998\n| 34<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/apress.html |title=Rocklist.net..''Alternative Press''.. |work=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| US\n| Top 100 Albums of the 1990s\n| 1999\n| 12<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/5923-top-100-albums-of-the-1990s/9/ |title=Staff Lists: Top 100 Albums of the 1990s <nowiki>| Features |</nowiki> Pitchfork |date=November 17, 2003 |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Melody Maker]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| All Time Top 100 Albums\n| 2000\n| 55<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/maker100.htm |title=Rocklist.net...''Melody Maker'' Top 100 Albums \u2013 2000 ..... |work=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[NME]]''\n| UK\n| 100 Best Albums\n| 2003\n| 53<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/nmes_100_best_albums.htm |title=Rocklist.net...''NME'' Writers Lists... |work=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=October 13, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| US\n| 100 Greatest Albums, 1985\u20132005\n| 2005\n| 94<ref name=\"Spin 100\" />\n|}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Discogs master|38099|type=album}}\n*{{Musicbrainz release group|e9f4b96a-94df-36be-9659-c9a811caead6}}\n{{Featured article}}\n\n{{Slint}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:1991 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Brian Paulson]]\n[[Category:Slint albums]]\n[[Category:Touch and Go Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "KevindeAmsterdam", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spiderland"}
{"title_page": "Mid-States Football Association", "text_new": "{{Infobox Athletic Conference\n|name = Mid-States Football Association\n|short_name = MSFA\n|established = 1993\n|logo = Mid-States Football Association logo.jpg\n|logo_size = 180\n|association  = [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]]\n|division =\n|subdivision =\n|members = 14 (15 in 2020)\n|sports = Football only\n|mens = \n|womens = \n|region = [[Midwestern United States]]\n|former_names =\n|hq_city =\n|hq_state =\n|commissioner = James D. Houdeshell\n|since =\n|website = {{URL|http://www.mid-statesfootball.org}}\n|color =\n|font_color =\n|map = MSFA-USA-states.PNG\n|map_size = 250\n}}\n\nThe '''Mid-States Football Association''' ('''MSFA''') is a college athletic conference affiliated with the [[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]].  Member institutions are located in [[Illinois]], [[Indiana]], [[Iowa]], [[Michigan]], and [[Missouri]].  The MSFA was organized in 1993, and on-field competition began in 1994. The MSFA is divided into two leagues, The Mideast and the Midwest. \n\nCharter members included [[Geneva College]], [[Lindenwood University]], [[Malone University|Malone College]], [[Olivet Nazarene University]], [[Saint Xavier University]], [[Taylor University]], [[Tiffin University]], [[Trinity International University]], the [[University of Findlay]], [[Urbana University]], and [[Westminster College (Pennsylvania)|Westminster College]].\n\nMSFA member schools have won eight NAIA National Championships since the inception of the league in 1993.  An MSFA team has played in each of the last seven championships, winning six of the seven, including each of the last three.  The two MSFA division champions earn an automatic bid to the NAIA National Championship Series.\n\n==National Championship appearances==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:60%;\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#b31f2b; color:white;\" |Year\n!style=\"background:#b31f2b; color:white;\" |MSFA Member\n!style=\"background:#b31f2b; color:white;\" |Opponent\n!style=\"background:#b31f2b; color:white;\" |Result\n!style=\"background:#b31f2b; color:white;\" |Score\n\n|- style=\"background:#ff7f00; text-align:center;\"\n|[[1995 NAIA Football National Championship|'''1995''']]||[[Findlay Oilers football|'''Findlay (OH)''']] ||[[Central Washington Wildcats football|'''Central Washington''']]||'''Tie''' ||'''21-21'''\n|- style=\"background:#ff7f00; text-align:center;\"\n|[[1997 NAIA Football National Championship|'''1997''']]||[[Findlay Oilers football|'''Findlay (OH)''']] ||[[Willamette Bearcats football|'''Willamette''']]||'''Won''' ||'''14-7'''\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[1998 NAIA Football National Championship|1998]]||[[Olivet Nazarene Tigers football|Olivet Nazarene (IL)]]|||[[Azusa Pacific Cougars football|Azusa Pacific (CA)]]||Lost||17-14\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[2004 NAIA Football National Championship|2004]]||[[Saint Francis Cougars football|Saint Francis (IN)]]||[[Carroll Fighting Saints football|Carroll (MT)]]||Lost|||15-13 (2 OT)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[2005 NAIA Football National Championship|2005]]||[[Saint Francis Cougars football|Saint Francis (IN)]]||[[Carroll Fighting Saints football|Carroll (MT)]]||Lost||27-10\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|[[2006 NAIA Football National Championship|2006]]||[[Saint Francis Cougars football|Saint Francis (IN)]]|||[[Sioux Falls Cougars football|Sioux Falls (SD)]]||Lost||23-19\n|- style=\"background:#ffd800; text-align:center;\"\n|[[2011 NAIA Football National Championship|'''2011''']]||[[Saint Xavier Cougars football|'''Saint Xavier (IL)''']]   ||[[Carroll Fighting Saints football|'''Carroll (MT)''']]||'''Won''' ||'''24-20'''\n|- style=\"background:#ff7f00; text-align:center;\"\n|[[2012 NAIA Football National Championship|'''2012''']]||[[Marian Knights football|'''Marian (IN)''']]   ||[[Morningside Mustangs football|'''Morningside (IA)''']]||'''Won''' ||'''30-27 (OT)'''\n|- style=